SIMPLE: imposition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imposition
<hw>Im`po*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>impositio</ets> the application of a name to a thing. See
<er>Impone</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of imposing, laying on,
affixing, enjoining, inflicting, obtruding, and the like.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧From <xex>imposition</xex> of strict laws.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Milton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Made more solemn by the <qex>imposition</qex> of hands.</q>
<rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is imposed, levied, or enjoined; charge;
burden; injunction; tax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eng. Univ.)</fld> <def>An extra exercise enjoined
on students as a punishment.</def> <rj><au>T. Warton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An excessive, arbitrary, or unlawful exaction;
hence, a trick or deception put on laid on others; cheating; fraud;
delusion; imposture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reputation is an idle and most false <qex>imposition</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The act of laying on the hands as
a religious ceremony, in ordination, confirmation, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The act or process of imposing
pages or columns of type. See <er>Impose</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>,
4.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Deceit; fraud; imposture. See
<er>Deception</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impossibility</ent>⟦br⟧
